 {"id":"asupersync-8w83i.3","title":"[FABRIC][P2] Static Capability Layer & Cx Integration","description":"# Phase 2: Static Capability Layer & Cx Integration

## Purpose
Make capability possession a compile-time property for in-process Rust code and a runtime property at process boundaries. This is a two-layer capability architecture that goes far beyond ACLs.

## Static Layer (Compile-Time)
Rust ownership and typestate as zero-cost capability layer beneath Cx:
- PublishPermit<S>: owned non-Copy token consumed to publish to subject family S
- SubscribeToken<S>: owned token for registering interest in S
- SessionToken<P, State>: linear protocol-state token for typed conversations
- CursorAuthorityLease: owned authority for cursor operations
- AppendCertificate: owned authority for stream appends
- FenceToken: owned authority for fencing operations

These prevent stale-token reuse, missing permit consumption, and illegal local protocol steps at compile time.

## Dynamic Layer (Runtime)
- Cx integration: each subject prefix or transform space granted through explicit capabilities in Cx
- Capability grant lowers to both owned token type (in-process) and runtime check (distributed)
- Capability-checked routing programs for export/import plans
- The obligation ledger tracks capability grants and revocations

## Why Two Layers
- Static: prevents in-process misuse as compile errors
- Dynamic: prevents distributed misuse as capability errors, stale-certificate rejects, or obligation violations
- Neither layer alone is sufficient; together they produce the strongest practical guarantee

## Relation to Existing Code
- cx/cx.rs already has capability context, checkpoint/cancel/mask, macaroon attenuation
- cx/registry.rs has capability registry with commit_permit
- security/ module has authenticated, tag, context, key types
- This extends those concepts into the messaging domain

## FABRIC North Star Reference
This phase is governed by the five cross-cutting FABRIC success criteria defined in `src/messaging/mod.rs` and `docs/FABRIC_GUARDRAILS.md`:
1. Keep the public mental model NATS-small.
2. Make stronger guarantees explicit named service classes, never hidden taxes on the common case.
3. Lower radical behavior into small, inspectable artifacts.
4. Keep autonomous policy loops inside declared safety envelopes with replay, evidence, and rollback.
5. Target the first product wedge at systems that need sovereignty, durable partial progress, and post-incident explanation together.

If work in this phase violates those criteria, or drifts toward the anti-goal of a grand unified fabric that makes the common case slower and less legible than NATS, it must be redesigned.","status":"tombstone","priority":1,"issue_type":"epic","created_at":"2026-03-17T06:54:51.585291447Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-23T07:08:17.006726880Z","closed_at":"2026-03-23T07:08:17.006726880Z","source_repo":".","deleted_at":"2026-03-23T07:08:17.006678741Z","deleted_by":"system","delete_reason":"merge deletion","original_type":"epic","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["capability","fabric","typestate"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-8w83i.3","depends_on_id":"asupersync-8w83i","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-17T06:54:51.585291447Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-8w83i.3","depends_on_id":"asupersync-8w83i.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-17T07:04:45.674547643Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"asupersync-8w83i.3.1","title":"[FABRIC][P2.1] Define static capability token types","description":"Define the compile-time capability token types that form a zero-cost capability layer beneath Cx. File: src/messaging/capability/tokens.rs

- PublishPermit<S>: owned non-Copy token consumed to publish to subject family S. Must be consumed (moved) to publish — prevents reuse. Phantom type S ties to subject family.
- SubscribeToken<S>: owned token for registering interest in S. Consumed on subscription creation.
- SessionToken<P, State>: linear protocol-state token for typed conversations. P is protocol type, State is current protocol state (typestate pattern). Non-Copy, must be advanced through protocol steps.
- CursorAuthorityLease: owned authority artifact for cursor operations. Carries cell_id, epoch, and lease expiry.
- AppendCertificate: owned authority for stream appends. Carries cell_id, epoch, sequence.
- FenceToken: owned authority for fencing operations. Epoch-bound.
- All tokens: non-Copy, non-Clone (linear), carry metadata for validation, have Display for debugging
